					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">With how just about every modern processor is multi core, this is something that should be trivial to find, but it isn't for whatever reason. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_neutral.gif" alt=":|" title="Neutral" /> From what I've seen, most every multi core processor has at least two levels of cache; L1 is for each core, and L2 is shared by all of them. What I'm wondering, is how is L2 shared? Assuming we're talking about a dual core processor, is it that even cycles go to one core, and odd cycles go to the other? Or does each processor generally handle this differently? Of course, there's the issue of general external ram then; can each core even interact with ram directly, or must it perform a dma transfer to move the data in and out of cache in chunks?</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

